WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.770 --> 00:00:03.170
Welcome to Jeremy’s IT Lab.

00:00:03.170 --> 00:00:06.670
This is a free, complete course for the CCNA.

00:00:06.670 --> 00:00:10.400
If you like these videos, please subscribe
to follow along with the series.

00:00:10.400 --> 00:00:14.830
Also, please like and leave a comment, and
share the video to help spread this free series

00:00:14.830 --> 00:00:16.109
of videos.

00:00:16.109 --> 00:00:18.180
Thanks for your help.

00:00:18.180 --> 00:00:20.900
In this video we will cover security fundamentals.

00:00:20.900 --> 00:00:27.430
The CCNA is not a cybersecurity certification,
but it requires candidates to learn some fundamentals

00:00:27.430 --> 00:00:33.030
of network and system security necessary to
work as an IT professional.

00:00:33.030 --> 00:00:35.590
Here are the exam topics we’ll cover in
this video.

00:00:35.590 --> 00:00:41.420
We’ll define some key security concepts,
security program elements, talk about passwords

00:00:41.420 --> 00:00:47.680
and user authentication, and define the AAA
concepts of authentication, authorization,

00:00:47.680 --> 00:00:49.270
and accounting.

00:00:49.270 --> 00:00:52.170
That seems like a lot for one video, and it
is.

00:00:52.170 --> 00:00:56.690
This video will be a brief introduction to
a lot of different security topics.

00:00:56.690 --> 00:01:00.879
If you haven’t studied this material before,
there will be a lot of new terms to learn

00:01:00.879 --> 00:01:02.379
and memorize.

00:01:02.379 --> 00:01:06.360
So I recommend taking notes to keep all of
the information organized.

00:01:06.360 --> 00:01:09.810
Here’s what we’ll cover in specific.

00:01:09.810 --> 00:01:13.429
First I’ll introduce some key security concepts
and terms.

00:01:13.429 --> 00:01:18.729
Then some common attacks which can target
an enterprise’s systems and information.

00:01:18.729 --> 00:01:22.890
Then I’ll talk about passwords and multi-factor
authentication.

00:01:22.890 --> 00:01:29.200
Then the concepts of Authentication, Authorization,
and Accounting, also known as AAA.

00:01:29.200 --> 00:01:33.099
Finally I’ll introduce security programs
which should be implemented by enterprises

00:01:33.099 --> 00:01:36.880
to secure their systems and educate their
staff.

00:01:36.880 --> 00:01:41.579
Watch until the end of the video for a bonus
question from Boson Software’s ExSim for

00:01:41.579 --> 00:01:43.099
CCNA.

00:01:43.099 --> 00:01:47.569
So, the title of this slide is ‘why security?’

00:01:47.569 --> 00:01:50.639
What is the purpose or goal of security in
an enterprise?

00:01:50.639 --> 00:01:54.840
I’m sure you can think of some reasons why
an enterprise would want its information and

00:01:54.840 --> 00:01:59.130
systems to be secure, but it’s good to have
a framework.

00:01:59.130 --> 00:02:03.270
The principles of the CIA triad form the foundation
of security.

00:02:03.270 --> 00:02:06.919
We’re not talking about the American Central
Intelligence Agency.

00:02:06.919 --> 00:02:10.450
Here’s what CIA stands for in this case.

00:02:10.450 --> 00:02:13.160
C stands for confidentiality.

00:02:13.160 --> 00:02:14.500
What does that mean?

00:02:14.500 --> 00:02:19.170
It means that only authorized users should
be able to access data.

00:02:19.170 --> 00:02:23.940
Some information and data is public and can
be accessed by anyone, for example information

00:02:23.940 --> 00:02:30.390
put on the company website, but some is secret
and should only be accessed by specific people.

00:02:30.390 --> 00:02:35.740
And there are degrees in the middle, some
information is more secret, some is less secret.

00:02:35.740 --> 00:02:39.420
Then, I stands for integrity.

00:02:39.420 --> 00:02:43.760
This means that data should not be tampered
with, should not be modified, by unauthorized

00:02:43.760 --> 00:02:44.930
users.

00:02:44.930 --> 00:02:49.360
Data should be correct and authentic, not
modified by an attacker.

00:02:49.360 --> 00:02:53.090
Finally, A stands for availability.

00:02:53.090 --> 00:02:57.160
This means that the enterprise network and
systems should be operational and accessible

00:02:57.160 --> 00:02:59.220
to authorized users.

00:02:59.220 --> 00:03:03.650
For example, staff should be able to access
the internal resources they need to perform

00:03:03.650 --> 00:03:07.870
their duties, and the company’s website
should be up and running and available to

00:03:07.870 --> 00:03:08.870
customers.

00:03:08.870 --> 00:03:11.970
So, that’s the CIA triad.

00:03:11.970 --> 00:03:16.200
Confidentiality, integrity, and availability.

00:03:16.200 --> 00:03:21.000
Attackers can threaten the confidentiality,
integrity, and availability of an enterprises’

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:22.260
systems and information.

00:03:22.260 --> 00:03:28.280
We’ll see how attackers do that when we
look at some common attacks.

00:03:28.280 --> 00:03:33.760
In addition to the CIA triad, there are some
fundamental security concepts you should understand,

00:03:33.760 --> 00:03:36.590
and these are explicitly stated in the exam
topics.

00:03:36.590 --> 00:03:43.250
First, a vulnerability is any potential weakness
that can compromise the CIA of a system or

00:03:43.250 --> 00:03:45.210
information.

00:03:45.210 --> 00:03:49.490
But keep in mind, a potential weakness on
its own isn’t a problem.

00:03:49.490 --> 00:03:55.350
The windows of a house for example are vulnerabilities,
potential weaknesses, but houses continue

00:03:55.350 --> 00:03:56.810
to have windows.

00:03:56.810 --> 00:04:03.650
Next, an exploit is something that can potentially
be used to exploit the vulnerability.

00:04:03.650 --> 00:04:07.960
But again, something that can potentially
be used as an exploit isn’t a problem on

00:04:07.960 --> 00:04:09.160
it’s own.

00:04:09.160 --> 00:04:15.170
A rock can exploit the weakness of a window
and be used to enter a house, but rocks aren’t

00:04:15.170 --> 00:04:16.170
problems on their own.

00:04:16.170 --> 00:04:22.029
Next, a threat is the potential of a vulnerability
to be exploited.

00:04:22.029 --> 00:04:23.780
This ties it all together.

00:04:23.780 --> 00:04:28.699
To use the window and rock analogy, a threat
is a robber wants to use a rock to break a

00:04:28.699 --> 00:04:31.009
window and enter your house.

00:04:31.009 --> 00:04:33.470
Here’s a more relevant example.

00:04:33.470 --> 00:04:37.800
A hacker exploiting a vulnerability in your
system is a threat.

00:04:37.800 --> 00:04:43.629
Finally, a mitigation technique is something
that can protect against threats.

00:04:43.629 --> 00:04:47.400
There are various mitigation techniques and
they depend on the threat that is being defended

00:04:47.400 --> 00:04:54.330
against, and we’ll cover some techniques
in this video and the next few videos on security.

00:04:54.330 --> 00:04:57.840
Appropriate mitigation techniques should be
implemented everywhere a vulnerability can

00:04:57.840 --> 00:05:04.139
be exploited, for example client devices,
servers, switches, routers, firewalls.

00:05:04.139 --> 00:05:08.830
In addition, mitigation techniques include
things like preventing unauthorized people

00:05:08.830 --> 00:05:13.650
from getting physical access to the devices
by keeping them in a secure rack behind a

00:05:13.650 --> 00:05:16.529
secure door, etc.

00:05:16.529 --> 00:05:20.949
But always remember, no system is perfectly
secure.

00:05:20.949 --> 00:05:26.430
Systems can be more secure or less secure,
but there are no guarantees in security.

00:05:26.430 --> 00:05:31.830
You can, for example, implement malware detection
on your network firewall and have the best

00:05:31.830 --> 00:05:36.960
antivirus software on client PCs, but the
chance of the PCs getting infected with malware

00:05:36.960 --> 00:05:38.490
is never 0.

00:05:38.490 --> 00:05:42.810
Now let’s review some common attacks.

00:05:42.810 --> 00:05:48.039
These are threats which can potentially exploit
vulnerabilities to compromise the confidentiality,

00:05:48.039 --> 00:05:55.129
integrity, or availability, CIA, of an enterprise’s
systems and information.

00:05:55.129 --> 00:05:57.839
These are the kinds of attacks we will look
at.

00:05:57.839 --> 00:06:01.580
There are many more potential attacks than
just these, but these are some of the main

00:06:01.580 --> 00:06:03.099
attack categories.

00:06:03.099 --> 00:06:05.470
Let’s take a brief look at each one individually.

00:06:05.470 --> 00:06:10.930
The first kind of attack is the denial-of-service,
DoS, attack.

00:06:10.930 --> 00:06:17.089
DoS attacks threaten the availability of a
system, the A of the CIA triad.

00:06:17.089 --> 00:06:21.870
There are many kinds, and I’ll show a few
of them, but one common DoS attack is the

00:06:21.870 --> 00:06:27.270
TCP SYN flood, which exploits the TCP three-way
handshake.

00:06:27.270 --> 00:06:32.030
As you know, the three-way handshake is SYN,
SYN-ACK, and ACK.

00:06:32.030 --> 00:06:39.569
In a TCP SYN flood, the attacker sends countless
TCP SYN messages to the target.

00:06:39.569 --> 00:06:44.580
The target sends a SYN-ACK message in response
to each SYN it receives.

00:06:44.580 --> 00:06:49.050
But the attacker never replies with the final
ACK of the handshake.

00:06:49.050 --> 00:06:51.659
This final ACK is never sent.

00:06:51.659 --> 00:06:56.550
The target waits for the final ACK of each
handshake, and the incomplete connections

00:06:56.550 --> 00:07:00.180
fill up the target’s TCP connection table.

00:07:00.180 --> 00:07:04.219
The incomplete connections will timeout and
be removed from the table after a certain

00:07:04.219 --> 00:07:10.080
period of time, but the attacker continues
sending SYN messages to fill up the table.

00:07:10.080 --> 00:07:15.210
In the end, the target is no longer able to
make legitimate TCP connections because its

00:07:15.210 --> 00:07:20.099
has reached the maximum number of TCP connections
it can maintain.

00:07:20.099 --> 00:07:22.619
Let me demonstrate with a diagram.

00:07:22.619 --> 00:07:27.320
For each SYN message the attacker sends, the
target puts an entry in its TCP connection

00:07:27.320 --> 00:07:33.460
table and sends a SYN-ACK message, then waits
for an ACK to complete the connection.

00:07:33.460 --> 00:07:35.550
But the ACK never comes.

00:07:35.550 --> 00:07:41.279
The attacker keeps sending SYN messages, and
the target keeps sending SYN-ACK messages.

00:07:41.279 --> 00:07:47.229
Then the target’s TCP connection table fills
up, and the denial-of-service has been achieved.

00:07:47.229 --> 00:07:52.069
By the way, why do you think I drew the SYN-ACK
arrows not reaching the attacker?

00:07:52.069 --> 00:07:56.689
It’s because the attacker likely spoofs
their IP address, meaning they use a fake

00:07:56.689 --> 00:08:00.869
IP address, so the SYN-ACK messages don’t
return back to them.

00:08:00.869 --> 00:08:04.990
I’ll talk about spoof attacks after DoS
attacks.

00:08:04.990 --> 00:08:10.669
However, a denial-of-service like that is
usually not done by a single attacker.

00:08:10.669 --> 00:08:14.139
A much more powerful kind of attack is the
DDoS.

00:08:14.139 --> 00:08:19.649
In a DDoS, distributed denial-of-service,
attack, the attacker infects many target computers

00:08:19.649 --> 00:08:25.129
with malware and uses them all to initiate
a denial-of-service attack, for example a

00:08:25.129 --> 00:08:27.740
TCP SYN flood attack.

00:08:27.740 --> 00:08:31.059
This group of infected computers is called
a botnet.

00:08:31.059 --> 00:08:37.410
So, in this example the attacker could, through
separate attacks, infect these PCs with malware.

00:08:37.410 --> 00:08:42.760
Then, all together they start flooding the
target with TCP SYN messages, so the target

00:08:42.760 --> 00:08:47.650
server is no longer able to respond to legitimate
TCP connection requests.

00:08:47.650 --> 00:08:53.430
So, to summarize denial-of-service attacks,
they attack the availability of a system,

00:08:53.430 --> 00:08:57.640
the A of the CIA triad.

00:08:57.640 --> 00:08:59.880
Next let’s look at spoofing attacks.

00:08:59.880 --> 00:09:06.830
To spoof an address is to use a fake source
address, for example a fake IP or MAC address.

00:09:06.830 --> 00:09:11.800
There are numerous attacks that involve spoofing,
it’s not a single kind of attack.

00:09:11.800 --> 00:09:16.060
An example of a spoofing attack is a DHCP
exhaustion attack.

00:09:16.060 --> 00:09:20.450
Actually, it’s similar to the TCP SYN flood
attack.

00:09:20.450 --> 00:09:25.650
An attacker uses spoofed MAC addresses to
flood DHCP Discover messages.

00:09:25.650 --> 00:09:31.560
Then, the target server’s DHCP pool becomes
full, resulting in a denial-of-service to

00:09:31.560 --> 00:09:33.620
other devices.

00:09:33.620 --> 00:09:36.710
They won’t be able to get an IP address.

00:09:36.710 --> 00:09:40.940
Note that spoofing attacks don’t have to
be denial-of-service attacks, but this type

00:09:40.940 --> 00:09:42.300
is.

00:09:42.300 --> 00:09:43.910
Let me demonstrate.

00:09:43.910 --> 00:09:49.490
The attacker sends a DHCP discover message
with a fake source MAC address.

00:09:49.490 --> 00:09:53.050
Then it sends another with a different fake
source MAC address.

00:09:53.050 --> 00:09:57.100
Then it does it again, with another fake source
MAC address.

00:09:57.100 --> 00:09:59.760
It keeps sending these at a very quick pace.

00:09:59.760 --> 00:10:05.350
The server will reply to each Discover with
a DHCP Offer message, and while it is offering

00:10:05.350 --> 00:10:09.680
an IP address it will not assign that address
to other devices.

00:10:09.680 --> 00:10:16.220
So, if these PCs send DHCP discover messages
to get IP addresses, the server is not able

00:10:16.220 --> 00:10:21.290
to give them their IP addresses because its
DHCP pool is full.

00:10:21.290 --> 00:10:26.850
Maybe it had 250 IP addresses to lease to
clients, but they are all taken by the attacker.

00:10:26.850 --> 00:10:31.180
So, that’s just one example of a spoofing
attack.

00:10:31.180 --> 00:10:36.900
And in the previous TCP SYN flood example,
source IP addresses were spoofed too, so actually

00:10:36.900 --> 00:10:39.740
it’s also a spoofing attack.

00:10:39.740 --> 00:10:45.510
And this DHCP exhaustion attack resulted in
a denial-of-service, so it’s a DoS attack,

00:10:45.510 --> 00:10:46.510
too.

00:10:46.510 --> 00:10:51.470
As you can see, some of these attack types
are connected and related, they aren’t totally

00:10:51.470 --> 00:10:52.470
separate.

00:10:52.470 --> 00:10:57.900
But once again, we are attacking the availability,
the A of the CIA triad.

00:10:57.900 --> 00:11:00.300
Note that not all spoofing attacks are DoS
attacks.

00:11:00.300 --> 00:11:04.920
Later I’ll show another type of spoofing
attack that targets the confidentiality and

00:11:04.920 --> 00:11:09.730
integrity of a system, not the availability.

00:11:09.730 --> 00:11:13.820
Next let’s look at reflection and amplification
attacks.

00:11:13.820 --> 00:11:18.420
In a reflection attack, the attacker sends
traffic to what’s called a reflector, and

00:11:18.420 --> 00:11:22.880
spoofs the source address of its packets using
the target’s IP address.

00:11:22.880 --> 00:11:28.760
Then the reflector, for example a DNS server,
sends the reply to the target’s IP address.

00:11:28.760 --> 00:11:31.390
So, what’s the purpose of this attack?

00:11:31.390 --> 00:11:36.790
Well, if the amount of traffic is large enough
this can result in a denial-of-service to

00:11:36.790 --> 00:11:37.790
the target.

00:11:37.790 --> 00:11:43.360
But, there is a more powerful form of reflection
attack called an amplification attack.

00:11:43.360 --> 00:11:48.490
A reflection attack becomes an amplification
attack when the amount of traffic sent by

00:11:48.490 --> 00:11:53.300
the attacker is small, but it triggers a large
amount of traffic to be sent from the reflector

00:11:53.300 --> 00:11:55.360
to the target.

00:11:55.360 --> 00:11:58.510
This is how it can trigger a denial of service.

00:11:58.510 --> 00:12:00.110
Let me demonstrate again.

00:12:00.110 --> 00:12:07.940
The attacker’s IP address is 1.2.3.4, but
it uses source IP address 5.6.7.8 to send

00:12:07.940 --> 00:12:13.520
a message to a server at 8.8.8.8, which becomes
the reflector.

00:12:13.520 --> 00:12:18.500
5.6.7.8 is the IP address of the target of
the attack.

00:12:18.500 --> 00:12:23.350
The attacker’s message causes the reflector
to send a large amount of traffic to the target,

00:12:23.350 --> 00:12:25.770
resulting in a denial of service.

00:12:25.770 --> 00:12:31.960
For example, there are DNS and NTP vulnerabilities
which can be exploited for amplification attacks

00:12:31.960 --> 00:12:33.620
like this.

00:12:33.620 --> 00:12:37.080
You can check out these cloudflare articles
to read about them.

00:12:37.080 --> 00:12:42.730
Do a google search for ‘DNS amplification
attack’ or ‘NTP amplification attack’

00:12:42.730 --> 00:12:46.240
and you’ll find these articles.

00:12:46.240 --> 00:12:49.680
The next type of attack is the man-in-the-middle
attack.

00:12:49.680 --> 00:12:54.340
In this kind of attack, the attacker places
himself between the source and destination

00:12:54.340 --> 00:13:00.560
to eavesdrop on communications, or to modify
traffic before it reaches the destination.

00:13:00.560 --> 00:13:04.690
A common example is ARP spoofing, also known
as ARP poisoning.

00:13:04.690 --> 00:13:08.870
So, this is yet another kind of spoofing attack.

00:13:08.870 --> 00:13:13.840
In an ARP spoofing attack, a host sends an
ARP request asking for the MAC address of

00:13:13.840 --> 00:13:15.690
another device.

00:13:15.690 --> 00:13:22.240
In this case, PC1 is asking for the MAC address
of 10.0.0.1, which is SRV1.

00:13:22.240 --> 00:13:27.500
Because ARP request messages are broadcast,
the switch floods the frame, so both SRV1

00:13:27.500 --> 00:13:29.780
and the attacker receive it.

00:13:29.780 --> 00:13:35.410
Then the target of the ARP request, SRV1 in
this case, sends an ARP reply to inform the

00:13:35.410 --> 00:13:39.050
requester, PC1, of SRV1’s MAC address.

00:13:39.050 --> 00:13:40.980
But here’s the attack.

00:13:40.980 --> 00:13:46.420
The attacker waits briefly and then sends
another ARP reply after the legitimate replier.

00:13:46.420 --> 00:13:49.810
So, what’s the effect of this?

00:13:49.810 --> 00:13:54.750
If the attacker’s ARP reply arrives last,
it will overwrite the legitimate ARP entry

00:13:54.750 --> 00:13:56.720
in PC1’s ARP table.

00:13:56.720 --> 00:13:59.120
So, what happens next?

00:13:59.120 --> 00:14:05.660
Well, now in PC1’s ARP table, the entry
for 10.0.0.1 will have the attacker’s MAC

00:14:05.660 --> 00:14:10.380
address, not the address of the real 10.0.0.1,
which is SRV1.

00:14:10.380 --> 00:14:16.790
So, when PC1 tries to send traffic to SRV1,
it will be forwarded to the attacker instead.

00:14:16.790 --> 00:14:21.870
Then, the attacker can inspect the messages,
read their contents and then forward them

00:14:21.870 --> 00:14:23.530
on to SRV1.

00:14:23.530 --> 00:14:28.920
Or, another possibility is that the attacker
can also modify the messages before forwarding

00:14:28.920 --> 00:14:30.560
them to SRV1.

00:14:30.560 --> 00:14:36.910
So, in this example the threat isn’t to
the availability of the CIA triad, this kind

00:14:36.910 --> 00:14:43.000
of attack compromises the confidentiality
and integrity, the C and I of the CIA triad,

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:47.050
of the communications between PC1 and SRV1.

00:14:47.050 --> 00:14:52.430
It compromises the confidentiality because
an unauthorized user, the attacker, has access

00:14:52.430 --> 00:14:56.190
to the communications between PC1 and SRV1.

00:14:56.190 --> 00:15:01.040
And it compromises the integrity because that
unauthorized user can also modify the data

00:15:01.040 --> 00:15:04.790
before it reaches the destination.

00:15:04.790 --> 00:15:07.790
Next let’s look at reconnaissance attacks.

00:15:07.790 --> 00:15:11.960
These attacks aren’t attacks themselves,
but they are used to gather information about

00:15:11.960 --> 00:15:16.050
a target which can be used for a future attack.

00:15:16.050 --> 00:15:21.210
This is often publicly available information,
which is why it’s not really an attack itself,

00:15:21.210 --> 00:15:24.290
the information isn’t actually confidential.

00:15:24.290 --> 00:15:29.730
For example, you can perform an NSLOOKUP to
learn the IP address of a site.

00:15:29.730 --> 00:15:34.720
From there, you can probe for open ports which
are potential vulnerabilities.

00:15:34.720 --> 00:15:40.910
You could also perform a WHOIS query to learn
email addresses, phone numbers, physical addresses,

00:15:40.910 --> 00:15:41.910
etc.

00:15:41.910 --> 00:15:47.690
You can perform a WHOIS query at this website
here, for example I did a lookup of my own

00:15:47.690 --> 00:15:49.040
website.

00:15:49.040 --> 00:15:53.760
Once contact information is known, some of
the so-called ‘social engineering’ attacks

00:15:53.760 --> 00:16:00.060
which we’ll look at soon can be carried
out to threaten the target enterprise.

00:16:00.060 --> 00:16:03.420
Next up is malware, something you’ve probably
heard of.

00:16:03.420 --> 00:16:08.620
Malware, which means malicious software, refers
to a variety of harmful programs that can

00:16:08.620 --> 00:16:10.570
infect a computer.

00:16:10.570 --> 00:16:13.070
Here are a few types.

00:16:13.070 --> 00:16:17.680
Viruses are malware that infects other software,
called a host program.

00:16:17.680 --> 00:16:23.570
The virus spreads as the software is shared
by users, or downloaded from malicious websites,

00:16:23.570 --> 00:16:24.570
etc.

00:16:24.570 --> 00:16:29.750
Once the virus has infected the device it
can do various harmful things, such as corrupting

00:16:29.750 --> 00:16:33.440
or modifying files on the target computer.

00:16:33.440 --> 00:16:36.911
Then there are worms, which are different
than viruses in that they don’t require

00:16:36.911 --> 00:16:38.840
a host program.

00:16:38.840 --> 00:16:45.350
They are standalone malware and are also able
to spread on their own, without user interaction.

00:16:45.350 --> 00:16:50.070
The spread of worms from device to device
can congest the network, but in addition to

00:16:50.070 --> 00:16:55.130
that if the worm has a ‘payload’, other
malicious code within the worm, it can cause

00:16:55.130 --> 00:16:59.270
additional harm to target devices.

00:16:59.270 --> 00:17:03.590
Another famous kind of malware is the trojan
horse, which is harmful software disguised

00:17:03.590 --> 00:17:06.250
as legitimate software.

00:17:06.250 --> 00:17:11.650
Trojan horses spread through user interaction
such as opening email attachments or downloading

00:17:11.650 --> 00:17:15.180
a file from the Internet.

00:17:15.180 --> 00:17:19.209
Note that these types of malware are defined
mostly by how the malware infects a system

00:17:19.209 --> 00:17:24.610
and how it spreads, not the attacks they carry
out after infecting the system.

00:17:24.610 --> 00:17:29.360
The above malware types can exploit various
vulnerabilities to threaten any of the CIA

00:17:29.360 --> 00:17:31.920
triad of the target device.

00:17:31.920 --> 00:17:36.980
And as I said before, there are many types
of malware, these three are just a few large

00:17:36.980 --> 00:17:41.140
categories of malware.

00:17:41.140 --> 00:17:46.130
Next up is a very dangerous category of attack,
social engineering.

00:17:46.130 --> 00:17:51.630
Social engineering attacks target the most
vulnerable part of any system, the people.

00:17:51.630 --> 00:17:55.880
This is something you have to be aware of
when designing a security policy.

00:17:55.880 --> 00:18:00.950
No matter how many security features you configure
on your routers, switches, firewalls, servers,

00:18:00.950 --> 00:18:06.570
PCs, etc, people are always a vulnerability
that can be exploited.

00:18:06.570 --> 00:18:11.760
Social engineering attacks involve psychological
manipulation to make the target reveal confidential

00:18:11.760 --> 00:18:17.240
information or perform some action the attacker
tells the target to do.

00:18:17.240 --> 00:18:21.990
As with the previous attack types, there are
various kinds of social engineering attacks.

00:18:21.990 --> 00:18:24.590
Here are a few common ones.

00:18:24.590 --> 00:18:29.640
Phishing involves fraudulent emails that appear
to come from a legitimate business, maybe

00:18:29.640 --> 00:18:34.350
Amazon, your bank, or your credit card company,
for example.

00:18:34.350 --> 00:18:39.120
These emails contain links to a fraudulent
website that seems legitimate.

00:18:39.120 --> 00:18:45.220
For example, the website may look identical
to the real login page of your bank’s website.

00:18:45.220 --> 00:18:50.120
Users are told to login to the fraudulent
website, therefore providing their login credentials

00:18:50.120 --> 00:18:52.440
to the attacker.

00:18:52.440 --> 00:18:55.790
Spear phishing is a type of phishing that
is more targeted.

00:18:55.790 --> 00:19:01.500
Not mass emails sent out to anybody, but perhaps
emails sent to employees of a specific company,

00:19:01.500 --> 00:19:03.330
for example.

00:19:03.330 --> 00:19:08.430
Whaling is another kind of phishing targeted
at high-profile individuals, for example a

00:19:08.430 --> 00:19:10.730
company president.

00:19:10.730 --> 00:19:15.960
There is also vishing, voice phishing, which
is phishing performed over the phone.

00:19:15.960 --> 00:19:19.930
The attacker could pretend to be from the
target’s bank, or maybe another department

00:19:19.930 --> 00:19:21.510
in the company.

00:19:21.510 --> 00:19:25.770
They might say something like, Hi this is
Jeremy from the IT department.

00:19:25.770 --> 00:19:30.170
Due to company policy we need to reset your
password, could you tell me the password you’re

00:19:30.170 --> 00:19:32.140
currently using and I’ll reset it for you?’

00:19:32.140 --> 00:19:36.610
Now, I’m sure a real attacker would be more
convincing than that, but that’s just an

00:19:36.610 --> 00:19:38.500
example.

00:19:38.500 --> 00:19:44.380
Another kind is smishing, SMS phishing, which
is phishing performed using SMS text messages

00:19:44.380 --> 00:19:45.840
to the target’s cell phone.

00:19:45.840 --> 00:19:50.390
Okay, let’s move on from phishing, because
there are other kinds of social engineering

00:19:50.390 --> 00:19:51.430
attacks.

00:19:51.430 --> 00:19:56.970
Watering hole attacks compromise sites that
the target victim frequently visits.

00:19:56.970 --> 00:20:01.420
If a malicious link is placed on a website
the target trusts, they might not hesitate

00:20:01.420 --> 00:20:02.500
to click it.

00:20:02.500 --> 00:20:06.800
So, this kind of attack is taking advantage
of the user’s trust in the website they

00:20:06.800 --> 00:20:10.510
frequently visit, they don’t think twice
about clicking the link.

00:20:10.510 --> 00:20:15.260
Okay, I want to mention one more kind of social
engineering.

00:20:15.260 --> 00:20:20.670
Tailgating attacks involve entering restricted,
secure areas by simply walking in behind an

00:20:20.670 --> 00:20:23.590
authorized person as they enter.

00:20:23.590 --> 00:20:28.870
Any company that has restricted areas will
have rules against this, but often the target

00:20:28.870 --> 00:20:34.040
will hold the door open for the attacker to
be polite, assuming the attacker is also authorized

00:20:34.040 --> 00:20:36.250
to enter.

00:20:36.250 --> 00:20:41.010
To summarize social engineering attacks, they
are attacks that don’t directly exploit

00:20:41.010 --> 00:20:45.620
a company’s IT systems, instead they exploit
the employees.

00:20:45.620 --> 00:20:49.010
Here’s an example of a phishing email.

00:20:49.010 --> 00:20:53.590
It says that the target’s Amazon account
has been locked due to a suspicious login,

00:20:53.590 --> 00:20:58.770
and there is a link at the bottom requesting
that the target verify their account information.

00:20:58.770 --> 00:21:03.230
If the target clicks on that link and enters
their login information, the attacker now

00:21:03.230 --> 00:21:06.470
has access to their Amazon account.

00:21:06.470 --> 00:21:09.630
Anyone who has an email address has seen emails
like this, I’m sure.

00:21:09.630 --> 00:21:12.650
It’s something we all have to watch out
for.

00:21:12.650 --> 00:21:18.510
Okay, the final kind of attack we’ll look
at are password-related attacks.

00:21:18.510 --> 00:21:23.590
Most systems use a username and password combination
to authenticate users.

00:21:23.590 --> 00:21:29.130
The username itself is often simple and easy
to guess, for example the user’s email address.

00:21:29.130 --> 00:21:35.590
So, the strength and secrecy of the password
is relied on to provide the necessary security.

00:21:35.590 --> 00:21:40.400
However, attackers can learn a user’s password
through multiple methods.

00:21:40.400 --> 00:21:42.870
First of all, they could simply guess the
password.

00:21:42.870 --> 00:21:48.140
Now, successfully guessing a password should
be extremely rare, but it is a possibility.

00:21:48.140 --> 00:21:53.540
A dictionary attack can also be used, in which
a program runs through a dictionary, which

00:21:53.540 --> 00:21:58.190
is a list of common words and passwords to
guess the target’s password.

00:21:58.190 --> 00:22:01.690
It tries each one, hoping to find the correct
password.

00:22:01.690 --> 00:22:07.270
A brute force attack involves trying every
possible combination of letters, numbers,

00:22:07.270 --> 00:22:11.260
and special characters to find the target’s
password.

00:22:11.260 --> 00:22:16.120
This requires a very powerful computer, and
if the password is sufficiently strong, the

00:22:16.120 --> 00:22:20.040
chances of it working are very low, because
it takes so much time.

00:22:20.040 --> 00:22:24.990
So, what makes a password strong, so that
it can’t easily be brute-forced?

00:22:24.990 --> 00:22:29.410
Well, strong passwords should contain at least
8 characters.

00:22:29.410 --> 00:22:33.110
Definitely not less, but preferably more than
8.

00:22:33.110 --> 00:22:37.830
The more characters, the harder it is to brute
force attack the password.

00:22:37.830 --> 00:22:42.590
A strong password should have a mix of uppercase
and lowercase letters and a mixture of letters

00:22:42.590 --> 00:22:44.700
and numbers.

00:22:44.700 --> 00:22:50.300
Also it should have one or more special characters
such as question marks, exclamation points,

00:22:50.300 --> 00:22:51.400
etc.

00:22:51.400 --> 00:22:53.980
Finally it should be changed regularly.

00:22:53.980 --> 00:22:58.400
Most enterprises will enforce rules like these
on their employees, but it’s also recommended

00:22:58.400 --> 00:23:03.300
that you follow rules like these when making
your own personal passwords.

00:23:03.300 --> 00:23:07.140
Okay, that was a lot of potential attacks.

00:23:07.140 --> 00:23:11.060
To help you review, here’s a basic summary
of each attack.

00:23:11.060 --> 00:23:14.780
If you want to know more about each kind of
attack, a Google search will give you all

00:23:14.780 --> 00:23:17.050
kinds of great resources.

00:23:17.050 --> 00:23:22.450
For our purposes, just a basic understanding
of each attack type is sufficient for now.

00:23:22.450 --> 00:23:27.360
So, make sure you know these basic attack
types.

00:23:27.360 --> 00:23:31.540
Next let’s continue with the topic of multi-factor
authentication.

00:23:31.540 --> 00:23:35.820
No matter how secure the password, there is
still a chance it gets into the hands of an

00:23:35.820 --> 00:23:36.820
attacker.

00:23:36.820 --> 00:23:42.190
That’s why multi-factor authentication is
becoming more and more wide-spread.

00:23:42.190 --> 00:23:45.910
Multi-factor authentication involves providing
more than just a username and password to

00:23:45.910 --> 00:23:47.940
prove your identity.

00:23:47.940 --> 00:23:53.770
It usually involves providing two of the following,
in which case it’s called two-factor authentication.

00:23:53.770 --> 00:23:59.710
First is something you know, for example a
username and password combination or a PIN.

00:23:59.710 --> 00:24:04.440
Next is something you have, for example pressing
a notification that appears on your phone

00:24:04.440 --> 00:24:09.530
using an authenticator app, or perhaps a badge
that is scanned.

00:24:09.530 --> 00:24:14.210
The third is something you are, these are
unique characteristics about you.

00:24:14.210 --> 00:24:21.130
For example, biometrics such as a face scan,
palm scan, fingerprint scan, retina scan,

00:24:21.130 --> 00:24:22.280
etc.

00:24:22.280 --> 00:24:27.630
Requiring multiple factors of authentication
greatly increases the security.

00:24:27.630 --> 00:24:31.520
Even if an attacker learns the target’s
password, they won’t be able to login to

00:24:31.520 --> 00:24:35.150
the target’s account.

00:24:35.150 --> 00:24:39.490
Another form of authentication involves the
use of digital certificates, which are used

00:24:39.490 --> 00:24:43.700
to prove the identity of the holder of the
certificate.

00:24:43.700 --> 00:24:48.780
They are mainly, but not exclusively, used
for websites to verify that the website being

00:24:48.780 --> 00:24:51.560
accessed is legitimate.

00:24:51.560 --> 00:24:57.520
Entities that want a certificate, for example
a company with a website, send a CSR, certificate

00:24:57.520 --> 00:25:05.110
signing request, to a CA, certificate authority,
which will generate and sign the certificate.

00:25:05.110 --> 00:25:09.580
When you access a website, modern browsers
display a symbol here to indicate that the

00:25:09.580 --> 00:25:13.450
website is secure and has a valid certificate.

00:25:13.450 --> 00:25:18.390
As you can see, my website has a valid certificate,
and if you click on it you will be able to

00:25:18.390 --> 00:25:20.990
inspect the certificate.

00:25:20.990 --> 00:25:26.160
This is how you can know that the website
you’re accessing is really jeremysitlab.com,

00:25:26.160 --> 00:25:29.080
not a fake website pretending to be jeremysitlab.com.

00:25:29.080 --> 00:25:35.750
I’ve been mentioning authentication a lot,
and that’s one part of an important framework

00:25:35.750 --> 00:25:38.040
you need to know for the CCNA.

00:25:38.040 --> 00:25:43.010
AAA stands for Authentication, Authorization,
and Accounting.

00:25:43.010 --> 00:25:49.000
It’s a framework for controlling and monitoring
users of a computer system, such as a network.

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:52.820
So, what do each of those A’s mean?

00:25:52.820 --> 00:25:56.410
Authentication is the process of verifying
a user’s identity.

00:25:56.410 --> 00:26:02.450
When a user logs in, ideally using multi-factor
authentication, that’s authentication.

00:26:02.450 --> 00:26:08.290
Then, Authorization is the process of granting
the user the appropriate access and permissions.

00:26:08.290 --> 00:26:13.660
So, granting the user access to some files
and services, but restricting access to other

00:26:13.660 --> 00:26:17.220
files and services, is authorization.

00:26:17.220 --> 00:26:22.929
Finally, accounting is the process of recording
the user’s activities on the system.

00:26:22.929 --> 00:26:28.440
For example, logging when a user makes a change
to a file, or recording when a users logs

00:26:28.440 --> 00:26:32.230
in or logs out, is accounting.

00:26:32.230 --> 00:26:37.170
Enterprises typically use a AAA server to
provide AAA services.

00:26:37.170 --> 00:26:43.100
ISE, Identity Services Engine, is Cisco’s
AAA server, for example.

00:26:43.100 --> 00:26:47.700
These AAA servers typically support the following
two AAA protocols.

00:26:47.700 --> 00:26:54.920
RADIUS, which is an open standard protocol
and uses UDP ports 1812 and 1813.

00:26:54.920 --> 00:27:02.010
And TACACS+, which is a Cisco proprietary
protocol and uses TCP port 49.

00:27:02.010 --> 00:27:06.480
Just in case, I recommend remembering the
names of these protocols and their ports,

00:27:06.480 --> 00:27:09.820
but for the CCNA that’s all you need to
know about them.

00:27:09.820 --> 00:27:14.860
However, make sure you know the differences
between authentication, authorization, and

00:27:14.860 --> 00:27:15.860
accounting.

00:27:15.860 --> 00:27:19.610
They are stated directly in the exam topics
list.

00:27:19.610 --> 00:27:24.670
Okay, the final topic for today is security
program elements.

00:27:24.670 --> 00:27:30.830
A security program is an enterprise’s set
of security policies and procedures.

00:27:30.830 --> 00:27:35.080
For the CCNA, there are a few elements you
have to be aware of.

00:27:35.080 --> 00:27:38.030
First up, user awareness programs.

00:27:38.030 --> 00:27:43.590
These are designed to make employees aware
of potential security threats and risks.

00:27:43.590 --> 00:27:47.260
Not all employees are cyber-security experts.

00:27:47.260 --> 00:27:52.120
Someone working in the HR department is probably
not aware of all of the cyber threats the

00:27:52.120 --> 00:27:53.870
company is facing.

00:27:53.870 --> 00:27:59.710
So, user awareness programs will help make
those employees aware.

00:27:59.710 --> 00:28:04.480
For example, a company might send out false
phishing emails to make employees click a

00:28:04.480 --> 00:28:08.470
link and sign in with their login credentials.

00:28:08.470 --> 00:28:13.200
Although the emails are harmless, employees
who are tricked by the false emails will be

00:28:13.200 --> 00:28:17.800
informed that it is part of a user awareness
program, and they should be more careful about

00:28:17.800 --> 00:28:18.870
phishing emails.

00:28:18.870 --> 00:28:23.929
So, that’s an example of a user awareness
program.

00:28:23.929 --> 00:28:28.380
User training programs are more formal than
user awareness programs.

00:28:28.380 --> 00:28:34.490
For example, dedicated training sessions which
educate users on the corporate security policies,

00:28:34.490 --> 00:28:39.470
how to create strong passwords, and how to
avoid potential threats.

00:28:39.470 --> 00:28:43.950
These should happen when employees enter the
company, and also at regular intervals during

00:28:43.950 --> 00:28:46.110
the year.

00:28:46.110 --> 00:28:51.290
Another essential element of a security program
is physical access control, which protects

00:28:51.290 --> 00:28:57.010
equipment and data from potential attackers
by only allowing authorized users into protected

00:28:57.010 --> 00:29:02.480
areas such as network closets or data center
floors.

00:29:02.480 --> 00:29:06.919
This is not just to prevent people outside
of the organization from gaining access to

00:29:06.919 --> 00:29:08.530
these areas.

00:29:08.530 --> 00:29:15.179
Even within the company, access to these areas
should be limited to those who need access.

00:29:15.179 --> 00:29:19.169
Multifactor locks can protect access to these
restricted areas.

00:29:19.169 --> 00:29:24.290
For example, a door that requires users to
swipe a badge and scan their fingerprint to

00:29:24.290 --> 00:29:25.290
enter.

00:29:25.290 --> 00:29:30.940
That’s something you have, a badge, and
something you are, your fingerprint.

00:29:30.940 --> 00:29:36.690
Badge systems are very flexible, and permissions
granted to a badge can easily be changed.

00:29:36.690 --> 00:29:41.490
For example, permissions can be easily removed
when an employee leaves the company, whether

00:29:41.490 --> 00:29:44.130
they return the badge or not.

00:29:44.130 --> 00:29:49.520
This allows for strict, centralized control
of who is authorized to enter where.

00:29:49.520 --> 00:29:54.730
Okay, before moving on to the quiz let’s
review what we covered.

00:29:54.730 --> 00:30:00.559
First we covered some key security concepts
including the CIA triad as well as vulnerabilities,

00:30:00.559 --> 00:30:04.780
exploits, threats, and mitigation techniques.

00:30:04.780 --> 00:30:09.320
Then we looked at some common attacks, from
common network attacks to social engineering

00:30:09.320 --> 00:30:13.150
attacks which target people, not devices.

00:30:13.150 --> 00:30:17.380
Then passwords and multi-factor authentication,
which includes a combination of something

00:30:17.380 --> 00:30:21.390
you know, something you have, and something
you are.

00:30:21.390 --> 00:30:24.360
Then I introduced AAA.

00:30:24.360 --> 00:30:28.330
Authentication is the process of verifying
a user’s identity.

00:30:28.330 --> 00:30:33.540
Authorization is the process of controlling
what that user is allowed to do in the system.

00:30:33.540 --> 00:30:38.060
And accounting is keeping track of what the
user does.

00:30:38.060 --> 00:30:43.990
Finally I introduced some elements of an enterprise’s
security programs, such as user awareness,

00:30:43.990 --> 00:30:46.549
user training, and physical access control.

00:30:46.549 --> 00:30:49.220
So, that was a lot to cover.

00:30:49.220 --> 00:30:53.390
But if you learn the information in this video,
you should be ready to answer questions about

00:30:53.390 --> 00:30:55.840
any of these exam topics.

00:30:55.840 --> 00:31:00.010
In the next few videos we’ll take a closer
look at some network attacks and what we can

00:31:00.010 --> 00:31:02.110
do to stop them.

00:31:02.110 --> 00:31:06.539
Make sure to watch until the end of the quiz
for a bonus practice question from Boson Software’s

00:31:06.539 --> 00:31:07.990
ExSim for CCNA.

00:31:07.990 --> 00:31:13.160
Okay, let’s go to question 1 of the quiz.

00:31:13.160 --> 00:31:19.170
Which part of the CIA triad ensures that systems
are running and accessible by users?

00:31:19.170 --> 00:31:25.030
Pause the video now to look at the options
and select the best answer.

00:31:25.030 --> 00:31:32.410
Okay, the best answer is D, availability,
which means that systems should be operational

00:31:32.410 --> 00:31:34.820
and accessible by users.

00:31:34.820 --> 00:31:40.620
A, confidentiality, means that data should
only be accessible by authorized users.

00:31:40.620 --> 00:31:45.510
B, integrity, means that data should only
be modified by authorized users.

00:31:45.510 --> 00:31:50.929
C, E, and F are aspects of AAA, not the CIA
triad.

00:31:50.929 --> 00:31:55.390
Okay, let’s go to question 2.

00:31:55.390 --> 00:32:00.140
Which of the following terms refers to the
real possibility that a potential weakness

00:32:00.140 --> 00:32:05.730
is taken advantage of to attack a system?
Pause the video now to look at the options

00:32:05.730 --> 00:32:09.250
and select the best answer.

00:32:09.250 --> 00:32:12.880
Okay, the best answer is A, threat.

00:32:12.880 --> 00:32:20.660
A threat is the possibility that a vulnerability
is exploited by an attacker.

00:32:20.660 --> 00:32:23.570
Mitigation techniques can be used to reduce
that possibility.

00:32:23.570 --> 00:32:28.410
Okay, let’s go to question 3.

00:32:28.410 --> 00:32:33.380
Your company implements door locks that require
a badge to be scanned and a pass code to be

00:32:33.380 --> 00:32:34.600
entered.

00:32:34.600 --> 00:32:36.150
What is this an example of?

00:32:36.150 --> 00:32:41.490
(select the two best answers) Pause the video
now to look at the options and select the

00:32:41.490 --> 00:32:44.559
two best answers.

00:32:44.559 --> 00:32:54.610
Okay, the best answers are C, physical access
control and D, multi-factor authentication.

00:32:54.610 --> 00:33:01.070
Physical access control allows only authorized
users to access restricted areas.

00:33:01.070 --> 00:33:06.430
Multi-factor authentication uses a combination
of things to verify a user’s identity, in

00:33:06.430 --> 00:33:11.060
this case something in the ‘something you
own’ category, the badge, and something

00:33:11.060 --> 00:33:14.020
in the ‘something you know’ category,
the pass code.

00:33:14.020 --> 00:33:18.500
Okay, let’s go to question 4.

00:33:18.500 --> 00:33:23.260
Which of the following is NOT an example of
multi-factor authentication?

00:33:23.260 --> 00:33:28.809
Pause the video now to look at the options
and select the best answer.

00:33:28.809 --> 00:33:36.950
Okay, the best answer is C, doing a retina
scan and then doing a fingerprint scan.

00:33:36.950 --> 00:33:41.500
Why is this not multifactor authentication,
even though you’re doing two things?

00:33:41.500 --> 00:33:47.480
It’s because the key of multifactor authentication
is that you use at least two different categories

00:33:47.480 --> 00:33:50.000
from something you know, have, and are.

00:33:50.000 --> 00:33:55.990
A retina scan and a fingerprint scan both
fit in the ‘something you are’ category,

00:33:55.990 --> 00:33:58.150
so this is not multifactor authentication.

00:33:58.150 --> 00:34:03.780
Okay, let’s go to question 5.

00:34:03.780 --> 00:34:07.770
Which of the following is considered Accounting
in the AAA model?

00:34:07.770 --> 00:34:13.270
Pause the video now to look at the options
and select the best answer.

00:34:13.270 --> 00:34:21.470
Okay, the best answer is D, logging the date
and time a user logged in to the system.

00:34:21.470 --> 00:34:24.830
Accounting is all about keeping track of a
user’s actions.

00:34:24.830 --> 00:34:30.000
A and C are examples of authorization, and
B is an example of authentication.

